<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson3_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Superposition and Gates</title>

<p>
Now you need to know how to calculate the outputs of gates when the 
inputs are in superposition, beyond memorizing that two H gates put a qubit into
superposition and then out again. To calculate the results, we need two pieces of knowledge:
<ul><li> How to visualize two qubit state</li>
<li> How to calculate the outcome when inputs are in superposition</li></ul>
</p>


  <section xml:id="sec-two-qubit-visual">
    <title>Visualizing two-qubit state</title>


    <p> As we learned before, the horizontal line divides between two different
    possible outcomes. If there is no line, then two different qubits are being
    represented. In the images below, the left side is a single qubit in 
    50/50 superposition. The middle depicts two different qubits, one  
    <m>\ket{0}</m>  and the other  <m>\ket{1}</m>. The right side depicts a two-qubit
    system with four equally possible outcomes. Each horizontal line divides between 
    each possibility of the two-qubit measurement outcome.</p>

  



<sidebyside widths="10% 10% 10%" valign="top">
  
    <image source="Visual_Onebit_50_positive.png" width="10%" />
     <image source="L3-4-twoqubitvisual.png" width="10%" />
      <image source="L3.4-TwoQubitSuperposition.png" width="10%" />
  </sidebyside>
  
  <p><insert> Put in two checkpoint questions. The first has a visualized state and asks what 
  it means. The second has a description and asks which visualized state is correct. Play around 
  with where the horizontal lines are placed.</insert></p>

</section>
 <section xml:id="sec-calc-superposition-visual">
    <title>Calculating Gates with Superposition Inputs</title>

<p> To calculate gates in which the qubits are in superposition, there is a simple 
rule to follow: <insert>Apply the gate separately to each possible outcome, then combine the results.
Consider the two examples below for the NOT gate. </insert></p>

<sidebyside widths="25% 10% 30%" valign="top">
  
    <image source="L3.4-5050-to-NOT.png" width="10%" />
    <p> </p>
     <image source="L3.4-7525-to-NOT.png" width="10%" />
  </sidebyside>

<p>The solutions are as depicted below:</p>

<sidebyside widths="30% 20% 50%" valign="top">
  
    <image source="L3.4-5050-NOT-output.png" width="10%" />
    <p> </p>
     <image source="L3.4-7525-NOT-output.png" width="10%" />
